{
  "answer": "**In the *Manusmṛti* (Chapter 9), one key rule on a son's inheritance of property is that brothers must await the death of both parents before dividing the paternal estate, at which point they divide it equally among themselves (though with allowances for the eldest receiving preferential extras like the best items and an additional share).**[^1] **Explicitly, \"After the death of the father and the mother, the brothers, having come together, should divide the paternal inheritance equally; for they have no power over it while their parents are living\" (*Manusmṛti* 9.104), and the eldest \"shall take one share more\" among other perks (9.117).**[^2]\n\n**In the *Yājñavalkya Smṛti* (Chapter 2), a parallel rule states that \"After the death of the parents, the sons should divide the assets and debts equally\" (2.117), with no mention of preferential extras for the eldest.**[^3]\n\n**Yajnavalkya relaxes Manu here: while Manu permits (and details) favoritism toward the eldest brother—including the option for him to claim the entire estate (9.105) or at least superior portions and an extra share—Yajnavalkya mandates strict equality among all brothers after the parents' death, without such privileges (beyond what a living father might choose to do pre-death).**[^4]\n\n[^1]: *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 9, [translation](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/09/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *Manusmṛti* 9.104–117, [translation/#p-dc931c](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/09/translation/#p-5211c4) (equal division post-parents' death, with eldest's extras detailed sequentially).\n\n[^3]: *Yājñavalkya Smṛti* 2.117, [translation/#p-24be00](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/02/translation/#p-24be00).\n\n[^4]: *Yājñavalkya Smṛti*, Chapter 2 (\"Division of Heritage\" section), [translation](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/02/translation/) (equal post-death; cf. 2.114 for living father's discretion only).",
